any of several places called Stratton or Stretton, almost all named with Old English <i>strǣt</i> ‘paved road, Roman road’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘enclosure, settlement’. Stratton in Cornwall, which may also be a partial source of the surname, probably has as its first element Cornish <i>stras</i> ‘valley’.","English: variant of <b>Sturton</b>, a habitational name from Sturton le Steeple (Nottinghamshire), Great Sturton (Lincolnshire), Sturton by Stow (Lincolnshire), or possibly Sturton (Northumberland), all of which placenames share the same etymology and early spellings as 1 above.","Scottish: habitational name from Straiton (Ayrshire), Straiton in Liberton (Midlothian), or South Straiton in Logie (Fife), all named with Old English <i>strǣt</i> ‘street, Roman road’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’."]}]},{"name":"Matilda","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Latinized form of a Germanic personal name derived from <i>maht</i>, <i>meht</i> ‘might’ + <i>hild</i> ‘battle’. This was the name of an early German queen (  895–968 ), wife of  Henry  the Fowler, who was noted for her piety and generosity. It was also the name of the wife of  William  the Conqueror and of the daughter of  Henry I  of England (  see  Maud  ). The name was introduced into England by the Normans, and this Latinized form is the one that normally occurs in medieval records, while the vernacular form <i>Maud</i> was the one in everyday use. <i>Matilda</i> was revived in England as a learned form in the 18th century."],"variants":[{"name":"Mathilda","meanings":["Latinized form of a Germanic personal name derived from <i>maht</i>, <i>meht</i> ‘might’ + <i>hild</i> ‘battle’. This was the name of an early German queen (  895–968 ), wife of  Henry  the Fowler, who was noted for her piety and generosity. It was also the name of the wife of  William  the Conqueror and of the daughter of  Henry I  of England (  see  Maud  ). The name was introduced into England by the Normans, and this Latinized form is the one that normally occurs in medieval records, while the vernacular form <i>Maud</i> was the one in everyday use. <i>Matilda</i> was revived in England as a learned form in the 18th century."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705189,"age":9,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705190,"age":40,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Matilda Stretton was born about 1250, in Bradley, Derbyshire, England, her father, Hervey de Stretton V, was 68 and her mother, Alina le Campion, was 66. She married Sir Matthew III Kniveton about 1275, in England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 2 sons and 1 daughter. She died in 1296, at the age of 47."},"et":{"about 1250–1296":"umbes 1250–1296","1204–1292":"1204–1292","1246–Male":"1246–Surnud","1250–1296":"1250–1296","1248–1301":"1248–1301","1275–1322":"1275–1322","1275–1334":"1275–1334","1282–Female":"1282–Surnud","1183–1272":"1183–1272","1185–Female":"1185–Surnud","about 1250":"umbes 1250","1275":"1275","1296":"1296","1185":"1185","1272":"1272","1250":"1250","1282":"1282","1183":"1183","1292":"1292","1290":"1290","1259":"1259","1248":"1248","1204":"1204","ABT 1275":"umbes 1275","1334":"1334","1301":"1301","1246":"1246","1322":"1322","Abt 1275":"umbes 1275","Ashbourne, Derbyshire, England":"Derbyshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Stafford, Staffordshire, England":"Stafford, Staffordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Bradley, Derbyshire, England":"Bradle